      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen studying the distance between an object and its image, we place the image on the negative side and perform a subtraction of the values (<htcite0>). Now, imagine that you want to perform operations only on the left side of zero and reflect.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0ee05b85-85cb-44a8-a83c-fea5595308e8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Same, but different",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: There as here</b><br /><br />Could we use the same rules that we use on the right side of zero also on the left side?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_indigenous",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A Mesoamerican aid\n\nLet us return to an image we have from the site of Copán, in Honduras – America (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblStelaC\"><tr><th>West Side</th><th>East Side</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"><td><img id=\"CWest\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CWest', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaCBeard.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td><td><img id=\"CEast\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CEast', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaC.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Two sides of Stela C of Copán (<htcite0>). Photos taken on <htdate1>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Table 1** shows, on the left side (west, the direction in which the sun ceases to be visible due to Earth's rotation, i.e., where the sun appears to set), a bearded king. On the right side (east, the direction in which the sun appears due to rotation, i.e., where the sun appears to rise), we see the same king without a beard.\n\nAnalogously, when working with numbers, on the left side we will add a “beard”, represented by the negative sign (-), to indicate the direction we are going. However, as we shall see, the way of performing the operation will not change, as will be presented in the sequence.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Ao somar dois números negativos, temos como resultado um número positivo?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Quando somamos dois números negativos, estamos caminhando ainda mais a esquerda, logo não há como eliminarmos o sinal, e por isto o resultado final será à esquerda."
      }
   ],
